column67: Which forms of energy are present initially?
column72:
The correct answer is spring potential energy. 



Since I am holding the cube against the spring, the cube does not have any kinetic energy initially. Futhermore, to simplify the problem I will choose the initial height of the cube to be the reference of gravitational potiential energy (i.e. where potential energy is 0).



So, the initial total mechanical energy must consist entirely of spring potential energy.

column88: What is the final state of the system?
column93:
The problem asks about the highest height to which the cube will reach. 



The cube has long since left the sprint, so we don't need to consider the spring as part of the problem.



When the block reaches its highest height along the hill, what must the speed be? It has to be zero. If the block's speed was not zero it would continue to move higher and its current position wouldn't be the highest. OR it have previously been higher and it is on the way back down.



In any event, the speed of the block at its highest point must be zero. 



So, the total mechanical energy must be entirely due to graviational potential energy.

Therefore, the only form of energy present in gravitational potential energy.
